BT /F2 18 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 738 Tm (PacManDRL Project Report) Tj ET
BT /F2 14 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 702.0 Tm (1. Executive Summary) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 672.0 Tm (PacManDRL is a custom reinforcement learning project in which a Pacman agent learns to) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 657.0 Tm (collect pellets while avoiding a ghost in a 20x20 maze. The project was inspired by the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 642.0 Tm (Stanford CS229 Pacman reinforcement learning paper, but it was adapted into a focused) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 627.0 Tm (single-agent learning setup. In this version, Pacman is the only learning agent, while the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 612.0 Tm (ghost follows a deterministic rule-based shortest-path policy and moves at half of Pacman's) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 597.0 Tm (speed.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 573.0 Tm (The goal of the project is to train an agent that balances two competing objectives:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 558.0 Tm (maximize pellet collection and survive long enough to clear the board. To make this) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 543.0 Tm (possible, the project combines a custom game environment, a convolutional neural network,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 528.0 Tm (replay-based DQN training, curriculum learning, and practical stability improvements such as) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 513.0 Tm (target networks, reward clipping, randomized starts, and checkpoint-based resumption.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 489.0 Tm (This report explains how the project works, what architecture it uses, how training is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 474.0 Tm (organized, what design decisions were made, and why the system is relevant to real-world) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 459.0 Tm (sequential decision-making problems.) Tj ET
BT /F2 14 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 435.0 Tm (2. Problem Definition) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 405.0 Tm (The project models Pacman as a sequential decision-making problem in a grid world:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 381.0 Tm (- The environment is a maze with walls, pellets, a Pacman agent, and one ghost.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 366.0 Tm (- Pacman must learn a policy that collects as many pellets as possible while avoiding) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 351.0 Tm (  collision with the ghost.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 336.0 Tm (- The ghost does not learn. Instead, it pursues Pacman using shortest-path movement and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 321.0 Tm (  only moves every other Pacman step in the final target configuration.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 297.0 Tm (This creates a constrained planning problem under threat. Pacman must learn:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 273.0 Tm (- short-term movement decisions) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 258.0 Tm (- long-term path planning) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 243.0 Tm (- local risk avoidance) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 228.0 Tm (- trade-offs between reward collection and survival) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 204.0 Tm (The learning objective is not simply to maximize immediate pellet rewards, but to discover a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 189.0 Tm (policy that clears the maze while remaining safe.) Tj ET
BT /F2 14 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 165.0 Tm (3. Relation to the CS229 Paper) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 135.0 Tm (The project was inspired by the Stanford CS229 paper "Reinforcement Learning in Pacman.") Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 120.0 Tm (That paper explored multiple approaches, including tabular Q-learning, approximate) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 105.0 Tm (Q-learning, and deep Q-learning.) Tj ET
endstream
endobj
